@NODE Inside "Introduction"

@{U}@{B}Introduction@{UB}@{UU}

... or what is this good for!

Inside of this archive there is a small utility that allows a
constant monitoring of online/offline state of a SANA2 compliant
network device like e.g. ppp.device by Holger Kruse.

It was originally written with exactly this device in mind.
So the stupid name - PepperWatch ("ppp" in my native language
is pronounced somewhat like "pepper"). Still it should be able to
cooperate properly with ANY SANA2 compliant device.

Since the release of Holger's Miami package, his ppp.device
became of less importance to most TCP/IP users who usually use
only one, namely modem interface to connect their computers
to the nearest InterNET provider. Still there are some users
(like me) who have not less than three interfaces configured
under the control of AmiTCP at the same time - with the fourth
(ppp) being periodically put on/offline via a dialup line.

For those users and all the other who have already paid for
the ppp.device and AmiTCP protocol stack, there is no need
to use (and pay for) Miami.

Nevertheless all AmiTCP users know it was based on the UN*X
routines with no interactive GUI users in mind. And some times
it may become really annoying to open the shell and enter
some commands just to find out if the device is online or not.
Especially if the modem is not in sight...

The idea was born... there should be an icon on the desktop
clearly indicating the state of the device. So it is!

But there is more. It allows not only to monitor the state
of the device but also change it with a simple mouseclick.


In short:

- no more wondering about the state of the device.
- no more shell commands to put device on/off line
- no more separate icons or dock/menu entries for on/off
- no more wondering how long am I already online?

@ENDNODE Inside





