@NODE Setup "PepperWatch Setup"

@{U}@{B}PepperWatch Setup@{UB}@{UU}


Setting up the parameters for PepperWatch is done by editing
the TOOLTYPES of its icon.


DEVICE=devicename.device  ; Put the (case sensitive) name
                          ; of the device You want to
                          ; monitor
                          ;
                          ; example: DEVICE=ppp.device

DELAY=nnn                 ; Since the monitoring is realized
                          ; with periodical query of the device
                          ; using SANA2 events notification
                          ; scheme, here You can enter the
                          ; value for the delay between queries
                          ; Acceptable values are between
                          ; 10 (about five times a second)
                          ; and 100 (once per two seconds)
                          ; as it affects also the delays
                          ; between ituition messages polling
                          ; You won't want to put a very
                          ; high value here. Values between
                          ; 25 and 35 work best for me.
                          ; Of course You may put 10 here
                          ; but I think it's not necessary.
                          ; On the other hand putting a 100
                          ; here can be a waste of time...
                          ;
                          ; example: DELAY=25

ONLINE=command            ; place the full path to the command
                          ; with arguments used to put the
                          ; device online. The command should
                          ; return zero for success and nonzero
                          ; otherwise if used in conjunction
                          ; with the VERBOSE switch
                          ;
                          ; example: ONLINE=AmiTCP:bin/bootpconfig ppp0

OFFLINE=command           ; same as above, but the command
                          ; should be the one used to put
                          ; the device OFF line
                          ;
                          ; example: OFFLINE=AmiTCP:bin/offline ppp0

XPOS=nnnn                 ; xcoordinate of the left edge of
                          ; the button on the screen
                          ;
                          ; example: XPOS=0100

YPOS=nnnn                 ; ycoordinate of the top edge of
                          ; the button on the screen
                          ;
                          ; example: YPOS=0017

VERBOSE                   ; Turns on additional information
                          ; in the ScreenTitle. Name of the device,
                          ; it's state and online time (if available)
                          ; will be displayed there as suggested
                          ; by Marek Jablonski.

IMAGE=imagepath           ; No! there is actually NO such
                          ; TOOLTYPE! The image for the button
                          ; is taken from the program's icon or
                          ; NewIcon structure. But who knows
                          ; what the future will bring to us?


When the PepperWatch is running You may set and snapshot its window's
position using menu items. This is an alternative method to editing the
"XPOS=" and "YPOS=" TOOLTYPE entries. Perhaps more intuitive some
times.


The icon supplied with PepperWatch has original (MagicWB) as well as
NewIcon images built in. If You don't like them You may supply another
one as long as it's an icon of "tool" type, both normal and selected
images are present and You copy all the appropriate TOOLTYPES into its
structure. The icon images for normal/selected state will be used for
online/offline state images of the button gadget inside PepperWatch's
window. The @{"picture" system "MultiView >NIL: PepperWatch.iff5"} here shows a small portion of my WorkBench screen
along with my setup for PepperWatch.

You may run several copies of PepperWatch to monitor more than one device
(or the same several times if once is not enough for you) with different
icons for different devices too.

@ENDNODE Setup




@NODE Launch "Getting Started"

@{B}@{U}Getting Started@{UB}@{UU}

